Deploying DDIQ in ECC AWS using ArgoCD

  • Moyo Omoleye
  • James Igoe
  • Former user (Deleted)
Owned by Moyo Omoleye
Last updated: Jan 05, 2024 by James Igoe
3 min read

Accessing AWS Web Console

Access the ECC cloud to login to the AWS Sandbox web console at: AWS access portal refer to the following document Accessing AWS for more guidance.

Use the AWSAdministratorAccess management console to login - AWSInfraOps has limited IAM policies implemented. Install awscli, awssdk, then authenticate to the AWSAdminstratorAccess account.

Created an EC2 instance - t3.medium ubuntu, two volume disks root - 50GB and additional - 100GB for the database itself.

Add correct tags to EC2 instance created. It is extremely important that the database gets the label: ansible: mysql (this tells Ansible that this server is a MySQL server), client: internal (this tells Ansible which client's configs should be used for vault+backups). Also add env: sandbox (this tells Ansible that this EC2 is in a sandbox environment)

Now move on to create the new database and make sure it is assigned to the backup user service account. Assigning a service account to the database VM means it can access the bucket as the service account without explicitly specifying credentials.

Setup MySQL and backups on the new DB server

Clone ansible-config which contains the ansible roles, playbooks, and inventory file needed to deploy mysqldb. Follow the readme on the gcp-server-config repo - update pipfile and piplock to the latest version of python if you're having compatibility issues.

Once the database VM has been created, verify that you can see the new VM using the inventory script in ansible-config (you should see it under the mysql group):

ansible-inventory -i inventory-aws_ec2.yml --graph

If youre unable to find all dbs in the console, then you need to modify your ~/.ssh/config file and remove 10* from the configuration.

@all:

  |--@ungrouped:

  |--@aws_ec2:

  |  |--cac1-sandbox-db-01

  |  |--ecc-ddiq-db

  |--@mysql:

  |  |--cac1-sandbox-db-01

  |--@aws_region_ca_central_1:

  |  |--cac1-sandbox-db-01

  |  |--ecc-ddiq-db

  |--@aws_env_sandbox:

  |  |--cac1-sandbox-db-01

  |  |--ecc-ddiq-db

  |--@aws_client_internal:

  |  |--cac1-sandbox-db-01

 

You need to have the ansible-vault password setup. (1Password Password Manager for Teams, Businesses, and Families ). Create a text file with the password and set the env var ANSIBLE_VAULT_PASSWORD_FILE in your .zshrc file with the path to the password file.

 

Run ansible-playbook -i inventory-aws_ec2.yml aws-push-key.yml to push our public key to the created instance. Run the ansible -i inventory-aws_ec2.yml -m ping all command to verify you're able to reach your instance.

Once youre ready, install MySQL and the WAL-G backup client using ansible (in ansible-config repo point to particular playbook).

ansible-playbook -i inventory-aws_ec2.yml aws-site.yml --limit=NEW_DB_SERVER

Once MySQL has been installed, check that backup storage was configured correctly:

ssh into the DB and run below commands:

sudo su -

wal-g backup-list

# you should see something like "No backups found" if it can reach storage correctly

 

Deploying DDIQ to EKS using helm via ArgoCD

Authenticate to both the eks sandbox and shared-services cluster and create separate AWS profiles for both in order to have access to the context to view available EKS clusters. Refer to this link for more guidance: Accessing AWS

aws configure sso --profile NEW_PROFILE_NAME

aws eks --region example_region update-kubeconfig --name cluster_name

Configure your account for ArgoCD connectivity

(NOTE) All those configs already setup and dont need to be adjusted for the sandbox ddiq deployment.

If the deployment is taking place on a new account other than sandbox, you must configure it the same way weve configured sandbox to allow connectivity so the deployment via argocd-dev in shared services can take place as this is where ArgoCD is installed. Add the following terraform config files:

  • add new config like this to the account: aws-dev: argocd.tf

  • add this one as well to the map roles block: aws-dev: eks.tf | Lines 92:96

  • add the namespace to this list to get a namespace-wide netpol: aws-sandbox: eks.tf | Lines 91:95

  • add new config like this to declare the account in the root module and provision a knowledgebase. deployment: aws-sandbox: ddiq-ecc.tf

  • add account as a target cluster to the argocd module in aws-shared-services: aws-shared-services: argocd_dev.tf | Lines 45:56

  • add endpoint and cert values of your account: aws-shared-services: argocd_dev.tf | Lines 5:6

  • add the account_id, role_arn and define namespace as argo app projects: aws-shared-services: argocd_dev.tf | Lines 69:79

Deploy your ArgoCD manifest via the ArgoCD UI

Follow this link for guidance on how to create your manifest file to suit your specifications:

DDIQ-DEV

DDIQ-PROD

Once you have a .yml file with your ArgoCD settings for DDIQ, you can deploy it using ArgoCD.

  • Create an App in ArgoCD

  • Click edit as yaml

  • Copy/paste your ArgoCD manifest yaml file

  • Click save and click create

Deploy your ArgoCD manifest with the terminal

# install argocd

brew install argocd

# login via okta

argocd login argocd-dev.oneexiger.local--sso

# deploy app

argocd app create ddiq-test -f ddiq-test.yaml

Once youve reached this step, congratulations - you have deployed DDIQ. Verify the deployment was successful on ArgoCD UI at: argocd-dev.oneexiger.local
